arning and counts dropped alerts\n  - `drainQueue()` loops through queue calling `sendOneBatch()` until queue is empty\n- Configuration flag `--alertmanager.drain-notification-queue-on-shutdown` (default true) controls this behavior\n- `notifier/manager.go` Run method returns only after all pending notifications are drained\n\n**Cleanup Ordering:**\n- Discovery managers stop first (notification and scrape)\n- Notifier manager stops with queue draining\n- Rule manager stops\n- Web handler stops\n- Each service's Stop() function is called in reverse order, allowing earlier services to drain while later services are still active\n\n### Common Patterns\n\n1. **Signal Registration:** All three use `os/signal.Notify()` with buffered channels\n2. **Multi-Signal Handling:** Support for second signal to force exit (Kubernetes explicitly, others via framework)\n3. **Graceful Shutdown Mechanism:** \n   - Kubernetes: Context cancellation\n   - Grafana: Explicit shutdown methods with timeout context\n   - Prometheus: Service group orchestration with drain functionality\n4. **Timeout Protection:** Bounded shutdown time prevents indefinite hangs\n   - Kubernetes: Second signal forces exit\n   - Grafana: Explicit 30-second timeout (or service-specific like 10s for gRPC)\n   - Prometheus: Service dependencies ensure cleanup completes or forces stop\n5. **Drain Before Stop:** Important for notification/alert systems to avoid losing data\n"
